---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Base
  title="Why the Rankine Cycle? | Nuclear Rankine Cycle"
  activeNav="why-rankine"
  description="Why the Rankine cycle exists, why water is the working fluid, and every industry that relies on it — from nuclear fission to fusion."
>

  <!-- ── Page Hero ── -->
  <div class="page-hero" style="background:#16A34A;">
    <div class="inner">
      <p class="hero-eyebrow">Motivation</p>
      <h1>Why the Rankine Cycle?</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        From heat to electricity: why this thermodynamic cycle dominates power generation,
        why water is the universal working fluid, and who else uses it besides nuclear plants.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── The Heat-to-Rotation Problem ── -->
  <div class="sec-banner" style="background:#16A34A;">
    <h2 class="inner">The Heat-to-Rotation Problem</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="content-row">
    <div class="inner content-cols">
      <div>
        <p>
          Most primary energy sources produce only <em>heat</em>, not rotation. Nuclear fission,
          combustion, concentrated sunlight, and geothermal heat are all essentially sources of
          thermal energy. Spinning a generator is one common way to convert that energy into
          electricity, but the challenge is getting from heat to useful mechanical motion in the
          first place. The Rankine cycle is the dominant thermodynamic solution to that problem
          and has been for over 150 years.
        </p>
        <p>
          The key insight is <strong>phase change</strong>. When water boils at atmospheric
          pressure it expands to roughly 1,600 times its liquid
          volume.<sup><a href="#ref-1" class="cite">[1]</a></sup> Channel that expanding steam
          through a turbine and you have a practical, continuous, high-power machine. Condense
          it back to liquid, and the pump can return it to high pressure for a fraction of the
          energy cost of compressing a gas. Liquids are nearly incompressible. This asymmetry
          between pumping a liquid and compressing a gas is what makes the cycle efficient.
        </p>
        <p>
          Unlike internal combustion engines, which produce pulsed strokes, steam turbines are
          <strong>steady-flow devices</strong>. They operate at stable, continuous conditions for
          months at a time. A single large steam turbine at a nuclear plant can produce over
          1,000 MW,<sup><a href="#ref-2" class="cite">[2]</a></sup> enough electricity for
          roughly one million homes.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="callout callout--info">
          <div class="callout-icon">i</div>
          <div class="callout-body">
            <strong>Not just for electricity</strong>
            <p>
              Any application needing shaft work from heat can use a Rankine cycle. Marine ship
              propulsion, industrial drives, and spacecraft power systems have all used
              Rankine-based designs. But large-scale electricity generation is where it has no
              serious rival for high-temperature heat sources.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Why Water? ── -->
  <div class="sec-banner" style="background:#0891B2;">
    <h2 class="inner">Why Water?</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="content-row content-row--bg">
    <div class="inner">
      <p class="section-lead">
        Water is remarkably well-suited to this cycle. Its advantages are numerous and they
        compound:
      </p>
      <div class="prop-grid">
        <div class="prop-card" style="border-top:5px solid #D97706;">
          <div class="prop-title">Heat of Vaporization</div>
          <div class="prop-value">2,260 kJ/kg<sup><a href="#ref-3" class="cite">[3]</a></sup></div>
          <p class="prop-desc">
            Water absorbs an enormous amount of energy during boiling with minimal temperature
            change. This lets boilers transfer large heat fluxes efficiently and keeps the T-s
            diagram spanning a wide, useful temperature range.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="prop-card" style="border-top:5px solid #16A34A;">
          <div class="prop-title">Availability</div>
          <div class="prop-value">&sim;71% of Earth's surface</div>
          <p class="prop-desc">
            Power plants site near rivers, lakes, or coastlines for cooling water. Nine Mile
            Point, for example, draws from Lake Ontario. In industrial quantities, supply is
            never a constraint.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="prop-card" style="border-top:5px solid #1865F2;">
          <div class="prop-title">Safety</div>
          <div class="prop-value">Non-toxic, non-flammable</div>
          <p class="prop-desc">
            A steam leak is loud and causes thermal burns, but carries no chemical hazard.
            This simplifies safety engineering dramatically compared to hydrocarbon working
            fluids.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="prop-card" style="border-top:5px solid #7C3AED;">
          <div class="prop-title">Chemical Stability</div>
          <div class="prop-value">Stable to &sim;650&deg;C<sup><a href="#ref-1" class="cite">[1]</a></sup></div>
          <p class="prop-desc">
            Water doesn't decompose at operating temperatures. It's among the best-characterized
            substances in thermodynamics. Steam tables cover the full operating range with high
            precision (see NIST Webbook).
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Who Uses It? ── -->
  <div class="sec-banner" style="background:#0F2147;">
    <h2 class="inner">Who Uses It?</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="content-row content-row--bg">
    <div class="inner">
      <p class="section-lead">
        The Rankine cycle is the thermodynamic backbone of most large-scale electricity
        generation on Earth. Any industry that produces heat and needs to spin a generator uses
        some variant of this cycle.
      </p>
      <div class="app-grid">

        <!-- Nuclear Fission — featured, full width -->
        <article class="app-card app-card--featured">
          <div class="app-card-accent" style="background:#1865F2;"></div>
          <div class="app-card-body">
            <div class="app-card-head">
              <div>
                <div class="app-tag" style="color:#1865F2;">Most Relevant to You</div>
                <h3 class="app-name">Nuclear Fission</h3>
                <div class="app-type">BWR, PWR, PHWR, AGR, RBMK, and more</div>
              </div>
              <div class="app-icon-wrap" style="background:#EFF6FF; color:#1865F2;" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none">
                  <circle cx="24" cy="24" r="4" fill="currentColor"/>
                  <ellipse cx="24" cy="24" rx="18" ry="7" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/>
                  <ellipse cx="24" cy="24" rx="18" ry="7" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" transform="rotate(60 24 24)"/>
                  <ellipse cx="24" cy="24" rx="18" ry="7" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" transform="rotate(120 24 24)"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              Nuclear fission reactors generate heat by splitting heavy atomic nuclei, primarily
              uranium-235.<sup><a href="#ref-2" class="cite">[2]</a></sup> That heat drives a
              Rankine cycle. Two reactor designs dominate commercial nuclear power in the United
              States and differ fundamentally in how they handle heat transfer:
            </p>
            <div class="reactor-cols">
              <div class="reactor-box">
                <h4>Boiling Water Reactor (BWR)</h4>
                <p>
                  Water boils directly inside the reactor pressure vessel. Steam travels straight
                  to the turbine with no intermediate loop. The design is mechanically simpler,
                  but the turbine handles mildly radioactive steam and requires shielding and
                  careful maintenance scheduling.
                </p>
                <p class="local-note">
                  Nine Mile Point Units 1 and 2, along with the nearby James A. FitzPatrick
                  plant, are all GE BWRs on the shore of Lake Ontario near Oswego,
                  NY.<sup><a href="#ref-2" class="cite">[2]</a></sup>
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="reactor-box">
                <h4>Pressurized Water Reactor (PWR)</h4>
                <p>
                  Two entirely separate water loops keep the radioactive primary coolant isolated
                  from the turbine. The primary loop runs at ~155 bar,<sup><a href="#ref-2" class="cite">[2]</a></sup>
                  hot enough to boil, but pressure prevents it. Heat exchangers called
                  <em>steam generators</em> transfer energy to a clean secondary loop that
                  produces the turbine steam. PWRs are the most common reactor type worldwide.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              Other reactor types are in commercial operation around the world. Canada's
              <strong>PHWR (CANDU)</strong> uses heavy water as both moderator and coolant,
              allowing refueling at full power. Russia's <strong>RBMK</strong> (graphite-moderated,
              water-cooled) and the UK's <strong>AGR</strong> (gas-cooled) represent distinct
              design philosophies, and high-temperature gas reactors
              (<strong>HTR/HTGR</strong>) are being developed for both power and industrial heat
              applications. BWRs and PWRs, however, dominate U.S. commercial nuclear
              power.<sup><a href="#ref-4" class="cite">[4]</a></sup>
            </p>
            <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/basic-ref/students/reactors.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              NRC: Types of nuclear reactors &rarr;
            </a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Nuclear Fusion — featured, full width, directly below fission -->
        <article class="app-card app-card--featured">
          <div class="app-card-accent" style="background:#7C3AED;"></div>
          <div class="app-card-body">
            <div class="app-card-head">
              <div>
                <div class="app-tag" style="color:#7C3AED;">Emerging Technology</div>
                <h3 class="app-name">Nuclear Fusion</h3>
                <div class="app-type">Some designs use the Rankine cycle. Others may bypass it entirely.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="app-icon-wrap" style="background:#F5F3FF; color:#7C3AED;" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none">
                  <circle cx="24" cy="24" r="5" fill="currentColor"/>
                  <circle cx="24" cy="24" r="14" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="4 3"/>
                  <circle cx="24" cy="10" r="2.5" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.65"/>
                  <circle cx="36" cy="31" r="2.5" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.65"/>
                  <circle cx="12" cy="31" r="2.5" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.65"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              Fusion releases energy by fusing light nuclei (typically deuterium and tritium)
              rather than splitting heavy ones. The energy release per reaction is enormous and
              produces no long-lived radioactive waste. Commercial fusion plants don't exist yet,
              but several private companies are making rapid progress. The approaches to confining
              plasma and converting fusion energy to electricity differ fundamentally.
            </p>
            <div class="reactor-cols">
              <div class="reactor-box">
                <h4>Tokamak Confinement (Magnetic)</h4>
                <p>
                  A tokamak uses a donut-shaped magnetic field to confine a superheated plasma.
                  Commonwealth Fusion Systems (CFS) is building a compact tokamak called SPARC,
                  with a commercial plant (ARC) planned to
                  follow.<sup><a href="#ref-5" class="cite">[5]</a></sup> ARC extracts heat
                  from a lithium blanket surrounding the plasma and uses a conventional
                  <strong>Rankine cycle</strong> to generate electricity. Thermodynamically, it
                  would work much like a fission plant: high-temperature heat in, steam turbines,
                  electricity out. ITER, the international research tokamak under construction in
                  France, is the largest such machine ever built.
                </p>
                <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.cfs.energy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Commonwealth Fusion Systems &rarr;</a>
              </div>
              <div class="reactor-box">
                <h4>Inertial Confinement and Direct Conversion</h4>
                <p>
                  Inertial confinement fusion (ICF) uses lasers or particle beams to compress and
                  ignite a small fuel pellet. The National Ignition Facility achieved fusion
                  ignition in 2022.<sup><a href="#ref-6" class="cite">[6]</a></sup> Commercial
                  ICF plants would likely still use a thermal cycle to convert the resulting heat.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Helion Energy is pursuing a different approach entirely: rather than extracting
                  heat, Helion plans to <em>directly convert</em> the kinetic energy of the
                  expanding fusion plasma into electricity via a changing magnetic field. If
                  successful, this would <strong>bypass the Rankine cycle</strong> and its
                  thermodynamic efficiency limits. Helion has a signed contract to supply
                  electricity to Microsoft.
                </p>
                <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.helionenergy.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Helion Energy &rarr;</a>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Coal -->
        <article class="app-card">
          <div class="app-card-accent" style="background:#DC2626;"></div>
          <div class="app-card-body">
            <div class="app-card-head">
              <div>
                <div class="app-tag" style="color:#DC2626;">Fossil Fuel</div>
                <h3 class="app-name">Coal</h3>
                <div class="app-type">Pulverized coal boiler plants</div>
              </div>
              <div class="app-icon-wrap" style="background:#FEF2F2; color:#DC2626;" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none">
                  <path d="M17 9L27 7L36 13L40 23L37 33L29 40L18 41L9 34L7 22L13 14Z" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.2"/>
                  <path d="M17 9L27 7L36 13L40 23L37 33L29 40L18 41L9 34L7 22L13 14Z" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                  <path d="M17 9L23 19L13 14" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                  <path d="M27 7L23 19L36 13" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                  <path d="M23 19L37 33" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.4" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <path d="M23 19L9 34" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.4" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              Coal plants burn pulverized coal in a large furnace to heat a boiler to approximately
              540&deg;C,<sup><a href="#ref-1" class="cite">[1]</a></sup> producing high-pressure
              steam for the turbine. Coal dominated electricity generation for most of the 20th
              century. In recent decades its economics have deteriorated significantly: natural gas
              became cheaper per BTU, wind and solar became cheaper per kWh in most markets, and
              environmental regulations on mercury, SO<sub>2</sub>, NO<sub>x</sub>, and particulates
              added significant compliance costs. U.S. coal electricity generation has fallen more
              than 60% since its 2007 peak.<sup><a href="#ref-7" class="cite">[7]</a></sup>
            </p>
            <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.eia.gov/energyexplained/coal/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">EIA: Coal explained &rarr;</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Oil -->
        <article class="app-card">
          <div class="app-card-accent" style="background:#92400E;"></div>
          <div class="app-card-body">
            <div class="app-card-head">
              <div>
                <div class="app-tag" style="color:#92400E;">Fossil Fuel</div>
                <h3 class="app-name">Oil</h3>
                <div class="app-type">Fuel oil peaker plants</div>
              </div>
              <div class="app-icon-wrap" style="background:#FFF7ED; color:#92400E;" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none">
                  <path d="M24 10C24 10 14 22 14 31C14 36.5 18.5 41 24 41C29.5 41 34 36.5 34 31C34 22 24 10 24 10Z" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                  <path d="M19 33C19 36 21.2 38 24 38" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              Oil-fired steam plants burn fuel oil in a boiler, mechanically identical to a coal
              plant but with liquid fuel.<sup><a href="#ref-8" class="cite">[8]</a></sup> Oil is
              overwhelmingly used for transportation worldwide, and using it to generate electricity
              is rare and expensive. Oil-fired plants that do exist typically serve as
              <em>peaking plants</em>, started only during extreme demand periods. They're expensive
              to operate and rarely run at baseload.
            </p>
            <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.eia.gov/energyexplained/oil-and-petroleum-products/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">EIA: Oil and petroleum products &rarr;</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Natural Gas -->
        <article class="app-card">
          <div class="app-card-accent" style="background:#EA580C;"></div>
          <div class="app-card-body">
            <div class="app-card-head">
              <div>
                <div class="app-tag" style="color:#EA580C;">Combined Cycle</div>
                <h3 class="app-name">Natural Gas</h3>
                <div class="app-type">Brayton + Rankine combined cycle (CCGT)</div>
              </div>
              <div class="app-icon-wrap" style="background:#FFF7ED; color:#EA580C;" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none">
                  <path d="M16 36C16 36 10 31 10 23C10 15 18 9 18 9C18 9 15 18 22 22C22 22 19 13 26 9C26 9 33 17 29 26C29 26 33 21 33 17C33 17 39 24 37 32C35 38 30 41 24 41C18 41 16 36 16 36Z" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              Natural gas combined cycle plants (CCGT) stack two thermodynamic cycles in series,
              achieving thermal efficiencies of 60&ndash;64%,<sup><a href="#ref-9" class="cite">[9]</a></sup>
              roughly double a simple steam plant:
            </p>
            <ol class="inline-list">
              <li>
                <strong>Brayton cycle (gas turbine):</strong> Compressed air and natural gas
                combust at ~1,300&deg;C, driving a gas turbine directly.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Rankine cycle (steam turbine):</strong> The gas turbine exhaust (still
                ~600&deg;C) passes through a heat recovery steam generator (HRSG), producing
                steam for a second turbine stage. The Rankine portion recovers energy that
                would otherwise escape as waste heat.
              </li>
            </ol>
            <p>
              Natural gas electricity generation has grown sharply in recent decades. The primary
              driver was the U.S. shale gas revolution: horizontal drilling and hydraulic
              fracturing unlocked vast domestic reserves, driving down prices. CCGT plants also
              start up and ramp quickly, making them a natural complement to intermittent wind and
              solar generation.
            </p>
            <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.eia.gov/energyexplained/natural-gas/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">EIA: Natural gas explained &rarr;</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Concentrated Solar Power -->
        <article class="app-card">
          <div class="app-card-accent" style="background:#D97706;"></div>
          <div class="app-card-body">
            <div class="app-card-head">
              <div>
                <div class="app-tag" style="color:#D97706;">Renewable</div>
                <h3 class="app-name">Concentrated Solar Power</h3>
                <div class="app-type">CSP — not photovoltaic</div>
              </div>
              <div class="app-icon-wrap" style="background:#FFFBEB; color:#D97706;" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none">
                  <circle cx="24" cy="24" r="7.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"/>
                  <line x1="24" y1="5"  x2="24" y2="13" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <line x1="24" y1="35" x2="24" y2="43" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <line x1="5"  y1="24" x2="13" y2="24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <line x1="35" y1="24" x2="43" y2="24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <line x1="10.2" y1="10.2" x2="15.9" y2="15.9" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <line x1="32.1" y1="32.1" x2="37.8" y2="37.8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <line x1="37.8" y1="10.2" x2="32.1" y2="15.9" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <line x1="15.9" y1="32.1" x2="10.2" y2="37.8" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              CSP plants use mirrors to focus sunlight onto a receiver, generating intense heat
              to drive a Rankine cycle.<sup><a href="#ref-10" class="cite">[10]</a></sup> This
              is fundamentally different from photovoltaic solar, which converts light directly
              to electricity with no thermodynamic cycle. Three main CSP configurations:
            </p>
            <ul class="bullet-list">
              <li><strong>Power Tower</strong> — heliostats focus onto a central receiver. Highest temperatures (above 500&deg;C). Integrates with molten salt thermal storage for after-sunset generation.</li>
              <li><strong>Parabolic Trough</strong> — the most widespread type. Curved mirrors focus onto a tube of heat-transfer fluid.</li>
              <li><strong>Parabolic Dish</strong> — individual dish mirrors focusing at a point. Often paired with a Stirling engine rather than a Rankine turbine.</li>
            </ul>
            <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.energy.gov/cmei/systems/concentrating-solar-thermal-power-basics" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">DOE: Concentrating solar thermal power basics &rarr;</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Geothermal -->
        <article class="app-card">
          <div class="app-card-accent" style="background:#DC2626;"></div>
          <div class="app-card-body">
            <div class="app-card-head">
              <div>
                <div class="app-tag" style="color:#DC2626;">Renewable</div>
                <h3 class="app-name">Geothermal</h3>
                <div class="app-type">Earth's internal heat</div>
              </div>
              <div class="app-icon-wrap" style="background:#FEF2F2; color:#DC2626;" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none">
                  <path d="M6 31H42" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <path d="M15 29C15 29 12 25 15 21C15 21 18 17 15 13" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <path d="M24 29C24 29 21 25 24 21C24 21 27 17 24 13" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <path d="M33 29C33 29 30 25 33 21C33 21 36 17 33 13" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              Geothermal plants tap heat from within the
              Earth.<sup><a href="#ref-11" class="cite">[11]</a></sup>
              In high-enthalpy fields (Iceland, The Geysers in California), steam rises naturally
              from the ground and feeds directly into a turbine using a dry steam cycle. In
              lower-enthalpy fields, hot water is brought to the surface and "flashed" to steam
              at lower pressure (a flash steam cycle) or an ORC uses geothermal heat to boil a
              working fluid at temperatures water can't efficiently handle. Geothermal's defining
              advantage over solar and wind: it provides <strong>baseload power 24 hours a
              day</strong>, independent of weather.
            </p>
            <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.energy.gov/eere/geothermal/geothermal-basics" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">DOE: Geothermal basics &rarr;</a>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div><!-- /.app-grid -->
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Organic Rankine Cycles and Waste Heat Recovery ── -->
  <div class="sec-banner" style="background:#D97706;">
    <h2 class="inner">Organic Rankine Cycles and Waste Heat Recovery</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="content-row">
    <div class="inner content-cols">
      <div>
        <p>
          When the heat source is at lower temperatures — roughly 80 to 350&deg;C — water becomes
          impractical as a working fluid. Boiling it at low pressures requires operating under
          vacuum, which creates significant engineering challenges. Organic Rankine Cycle (ORC)
          systems solve this by using refrigerants or organic compounds that boil at lower
          temperatures. The cycle is thermodynamically identical to a steam Rankine cycle: pump,
          boiler, turbine, condenser — just different working fluid and state-point values.
        </p>
        <h3 class="sub-head">Common ORC working fluids</h3>
        <ul class="fluid-list">
          <li><strong>Pentane</strong> — common in geothermal and waste heat recovery</li>
          <li><strong>R245fa</strong> — widely used refrigerant, effective from 80&ndash;150&deg;C</li>
          <li><strong>Siloxanes</strong> — higher-temperature ORC systems up to ~300&deg;C</li>
          <li><strong>R134a</strong> — low-temperature applications, often paired with heat pumps</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="orc-applications">
          <p class="orc-head">ORC is used in:</p>
          <div class="orc-tag">Geothermal wells (low-enthalpy fields)</div>
          <div class="orc-tag">Industrial waste heat recovery</div>
          <div class="orc-tag">Biomass combustion at moderate temperatures</div>
          <div class="orc-tag">Concentrated solar (lower-temperature systems)</div>
          <div class="orc-tag">Ship engine exhaust heat recovery</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="waste-heat-card">
          <div class="app-tag" style="color:#16A34A; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Industrial Application</div>
          <h3>Waste Heat Recovery</h3>
          <p>
            Steel mills, cement plants, glass furnaces, and refineries discharge enormous quantities
            of heat that would otherwise escape to the atmosphere. ORC systems can capture this heat —
            even at temperatures as low as 150&deg;C — and convert it to
            electricity.<sup><a href="#ref-12" class="cite">[12]</a></sup>
          </p>
          <p>
            The fuel is effectively free, since the industrial process generates the heat regardless.
            Waste heat recovery simultaneously reduces operating costs and carbon emissions, making
            it one of the highest-return energy investments in heavy industry.
          </p>
          <a class="learn-link" href="https://www.exergy-orc.com/application/heat-recovery-from-industrial-process/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
            Exergy ORC: Heat recovery from industrial processes &rarr;
          </a>
        </div>
